text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LanguageOfTheNacirema]]%0a%0a!Philosophy lessons from REST%0a%0a:Author: TimG%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aREST-based cultural analysis of the Nacirema %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aWhen one lays his head to REST, he RESTS his head on a pillow, or on the bare mattress. And when one goes on no more, we lay him down to REST in the ground, at least one RESTS his hope that possibility. But let's not REST there, we still have the REST of the way to go. One might REST his case in an argument When playing music, one takes a REST in a REST, only to play the REST of his part. And if it's a violin, he has his chin on the chin-REST the entire time, and the audience will REST their eyes upon him as he plays.%0a%0aFrom this usage of the word rest, we can see that the Nacirema culture is one of, well, rest. They find comfort in relaxation, and do all they can to remind themselves that comfort is near. Whenever something hard comes to an end, even a temporary end, they breathe a sigh of relief, for now they can "rest". Even their law takes a relaxed air, and their sports the same. Their entire culture is permeated by this break-taking belief.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210327-004542-450100#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Different origins for rest %0a-> - rachelc%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThe “rests” from this article seem to fall into two categories: the version of rest which relates to taking a break or sleeping and the version of rest which relates to the remainder of something. According to the OED, these “rests” have origins from two different languages. The first “rest” comes from the Middle English noun reste which is the same as the German word rast (which means dwell or repose). The second form of the word, on the other hand, comes from the French word “rester”, which means to remain or to linger. Therefore, these words are homophones but have different origins, which would make it extra silly for a Nacerima research to attempt to derive a deeper meaning from the two meanings that this word has. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210327-004542-450100#%0a#foxbegin 210503-011838-920810#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!What the polysemy of the word rest tells us about the Nacirema %0a-> - JasonE%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAnother possible interpretation from the polysemy of the word rest in the Nacirema culture is that the people of Nacirema are lazy, unmotivated and would prefer to do nothing than something that requires effort. Many of the meanings of rest have to deal with being stationary and inactive. From this we can tell that they are unmotivated and lazy as they would rather “rest their head on a pillow” than go to the gym and work out. Even in the case of doing an action, such as playing music, the violin player is said to be resting their chin on the chinrest the entire time and waiting for their break in the music so they can take a rest. Lastly, there is a high level of unemployment in the Nacirema society as the people who do not have a job would rather rest than put in the effort required to obtain a job.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210503-011838-920810#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema:)
